TY  - JOUR
AB  - Some of the interpretations of negative business savings presented by Humphrey in the June, 1938, issue of this Review are open to question. Increasing negative business savings, representing as they do a change in net worth, do not necessarily mean decreasing employment, and they may conceivably be accompanied by increasing employment. Surplus, although not essential to the incurring of negative business savings, increases their potential amount by increasing net worth. Surplus also affects employment because a firm with a surplus is likely to continue production longer than a similar one without a surplus; the plant of the former may very well be in better condition, and consequently it is apt to have lower variable costs and to be better able to neglect maintenance. Although dividends are not paid out of surplus, their payment is not unaffected by the existence of surplus. Retaining funds that could be used to pay dividends does nothing toward ensuring that those funds will be invested rather than hoarded.
