TY  - JOUR
AB  - The purpose of this paper is to discuss recent trends in the field of state regulation of public utilities. In the past five years there has been unusual activity on the part of state legislatures and regulatory authorities in this field. The objective of both has been, in general, to expedite the process of rate-making. As a consequence, much legislation of an experimental nature has been enacted. There have been in this period commission decisions affecting established practice and policy with respect to such matters as the rate-base, temporary rates, accounting regulations, affiliated interests, security issues, and the method of defraying the cost of regulation. It is obviously impossible even to begin to discuss all these subjects within the confines of a single brief paper. This discussion will, therefore, be limited to what in the opinion of the writers have constituted the most significant developments. These are: (1) the rate-base, (2) temporary rates, (3) accounting regulations, and (4) assessment of the regulated utilities to defray the cost of regulation.
AU  - Wilson, G. Lloyd
