TY  - JOUR
AB  - Stock market continuity is not adequately measured by dividing the number of shares traded on the New York Stock Exchange by aggregate daily changes in a stock price average. The decline in volume of sales per point of price change may have been the result in considerable part of the long-trend growth in the number and proportion of listed issues and shares of inactive investment stocks. Series of turnover in terms of total price changes are markedly cyclical in character, tending to vary with general movements of stock prices. A study of the period 1927-30 shows a striking decrease in turnover per point of price change in 1929 and 1930, comparable to the decline in 1937 and 1938. This type of measurement does not afford sufficient proof that regulation of the stock in market thinness.
